# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-beam/apache-beam] Apache Beam is one implementation of the Dataflow model paper.
[src:apache-beam/apache-beam] The Dataflow model is based on previous work on distributed processing abstractions at Google, in particular on FlumeJava and Millwheel.
[src:apache-beam/apache-beam] Google released an open SDK implementation of the Dataflow model in 2014 and an environment to execute Dataflows locally (non-distributed) as well as in the Google Cloud Platform service.
[src:apache-beam/apache-beam] Apache Beam makes minor releases every 6 weeks.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] In computing, **batch processing** is the running of a software job in an automated and unattended way.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] A user schedules a job to run and then waits for a processing system to run it.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Typically, a job is scheduled to run at a configured time of day or when an event occurs or when computer resources are available.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] The term "batch processing" originates in the traditional classification of methods of production as job production (one-off production), batch production (production of a "batch" of multiple items at once, one stage at a time), and flow production (mass production, all stages in process at once).
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Early computers were capable of running only one program at a time.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Each user had sole control of the machine for a scheduled period of time.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] They would arrive at the computer with program and data, often on punched paper cards and magnetic or paper tape, and would load their program, run and debug it, and carry off their output when done.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] As computers became faster the setup and takedown time became a larger percentage of available computer time.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Programs called *monitors*, the forerunners of operating systems, were developed which could process a series, or "batch", of programs, often from magnetic tape prepared offline.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] The monitor would be loaded into the computer and run the first job of the batch.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] At the end of the job it would regain control and load and run the next until the batch was complete.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Often the output of the batch would be written to magnetic tape and printed or punched offline.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Examples of monitors were IBM's *Fortran Monitor System*, SOS (Share Operating System), and finally IBSYS for IBM's 709x systems in 1960.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Third-generation computers capable of multiprogramming began to appear in the 1960s.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Instead of running one batch job at a time, these systems can have multiple batch programs running at the same time in order to keep the system as busy as possible.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] One or more programs might be awaiting input, one actively running on the CPU, and others generating output.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Instead of offline input and output, programs called spoolers read jobs from cards, disk, or remote terminals and place them in a job queue to be run.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] In order to prevent deadlocks the job scheduler needs to know each job's resource requirements—memory, magnetic tapes, mountable disks, etc., so various scripting languages were developed to supply this information in a structured way.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Probably the most well-known is IBM's *Job Control Language* (JCL).
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Job schedulers select jobs to run according to a variety of criteria, including priority, memory size, etc.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Remote batch is a procedure for submitting batch jobs from remote terminals, often equipped with a punch card reader and a line printer.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Sometimes asymmetric multiprocessing is used to spool batch input and output for one or more large computers using an attached smaller and less-expensive system, as in the IBM System/360 Attached Support Processor.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] The first general-purpose time-sharing system, Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), was compatible with batch processing.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] This facilitated transitioning from batch processing to interactive computing.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] From the late 1960s onwards, interactive computing such as via text-based computer terminal interfaces (as in Unix shells or read-eval-print loops), and later graphical user interfaces became common.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation, both one-off jobs such as compilation, and processing of multiple items in batches, became retrospectively referred to as *batch processing*, and the term *batch job* (in early use often "batch *of* jobs") became common.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Early use is particularly found at the University of Michigan, around the Michigan Terminal System (MTS).
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Although timesharing did exist, its use was not robust enough for corporate data processing; none of this was related to the earlier unit record equipment, which was human-operated.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation remains widespread in computing, both for general data processing and for system "housekeeping" tasks (using system software).
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] A high-level program (executing multiple programs, with some additional "glue" logic) is today most often called a *script*, and written in scripting languages, particularly shell scripts for system tasks; in IBM PC DOS and MS-DOS this is instead known as a batch file.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] That includes UNIX-based computers, Microsoft Windows, macOS (whose foundation is the BSD Unix kernel), and even smartphones.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] A running script, particularly one executed from an interactive login session, is often known as a job, but that term is used very ambiguously.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] "There is no direct counterpart to z/OS batch processing in PC or UNIX systems.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Batch jobs are typically executed at a scheduled time or on an as-needed basis.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Batch applications are still critical in most organizations in large part because many common business processes are amenable to batch processing.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] While online systems can also function when manual intervention is not desired, they are not typically optimized to perform high-volume, repetitive tasks.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Therefore, even new systems usually contain one or more batch applications for updating information at the end of the day, generating reports, printing documents, and other non-interactive tasks that must complete reliably within certain business deadlines.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Some applications are amenable to flow processing, namely those that only need data from a single input at once (not totals, for instance): start the next step for each input as it completes the previous step.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] In this case flow processing lowers latency for individual inputs, allowing them to be completed without waiting for the entire batch to finish.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] However, many applications require data from all records, notably computations such as totals.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] In this case the entire batch must be completed before one has a usable result: partial results are not usable.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Modern batch applications make use of modern batch frameworks such as Jem The Bee, Spring Batch or implementations of JSR 352 written for Java, and other frameworks for other programming languages, to provide the fault tolerance and scalability required for high-volume processing.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] In order to ensure high-speed processing, batch applications are often integrated with grid computing solutions to partition a batch job over a large number of processors, although there are significant programming challenges in doing so.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] High volume batch processing places particularly heavy demands on system and application architectures as well.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Architectures that feature strong input/output performance and vertical scalability, including modern mainframe computers, tend to provide better batch performance than alternatives.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Scripting languages became popular as they evolved along with batch processing.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] A *batch window* is "a period of less-intensive online activity", when the computer system is able to run batch jobs without interference from, or with, interactive online systems.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] A bank's *end-of-day (EOD)* jobs require the concept of *cutover*, where transaction and data are cut off for a particular day's batch activity ("deposits after 3 PM will be processed the next day").
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] As requirements for online systems uptime expanded to support globalization, the Internet, and other business needs, the batch window shrank and increasing emphasis was placed on techniques that would require online data to be available for a maximum amount of time.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] The *batch size* refers to the number of work units to be processed within one batch operation.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] The IBM mainframe z/OS operating system or platform has arguably the most highly refined and evolved set of batch processing facilities owing to its origins, long history, and continuing evolution.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Today such systems commonly support hundreds or even thousands of concurrent online and batch tasks within a single operating system image.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] The Unix programs `cron`, `at`, and `batch` (today `batch` is a variant of `at`) allow for complex scheduling of jobs.
[src:apache-beam/batch-processing] Most high-performance computing clusters use batch processing to maximize cluster usage.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] In computer programming, **dataflow programming** is a programming paradigm that models a program as a directed graph of the data flowing between operations, thus implementing dataflow principles and architecture.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming languages share some features of functional languages, and were generally developed in order to bring some functional concepts to a language more suitable for numeric processing.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Some authors use the term *datastream* instead of *dataflow* to avoid confusion with dataflow computing or dataflow architecture, based on an indeterministic machine paradigm.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming was pioneered by Jack Dennis and his graduate students at MIT in the 1960s.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Traditionally, a program is modelled as a series of operations happening in a specific order; this may be referred to as sequential, procedural, control flow (indicating that the program chooses a specific path), or imperative programming.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] The program focuses on commands, in line with the von Neumann vision of sequential programming, where data is normally "at rest".
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] In contrast, dataflow programming emphasizes the movement of data and models programs as a series of connections.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Explicitly defined inputs and outputs connect operations, which function like black boxes.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] An operation runs as soon as all of its inputs become valid.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Thus, dataflow languages are inherently parallel and can work well in large, decentralized systems.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] One of the key concepts in computer programming is the idea of state, essentially a snapshot of various conditions in the system.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Most programming languages require a considerable amount of state information, which is generally hidden from the programmer.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Often, the computer itself has no idea which piece of information encodes the enduring state.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] This is a serious problem, as the state information needs to be shared across multiple processors in parallel processing machines.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Most languages force the programmer to add extra code to indicate which data and parts of the code are important to the state.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] This code tends to be both expensive in terms of performance, as well as difficult to read or debug.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Explicit parallelism is one of the main reasons for the poor performance of Enterprise Java Beans when building data-intensive, non-OLTP applications.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Where a sequential program can be imagined as a single worker moving between tasks (operations), a dataflow program is more like a series of workers on an assembly line, each doing a specific task whenever materials are available.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Since the operations are only concerned with the availability of data inputs, they have no hidden state to track, and are all "ready" at the same time.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs are represented in different ways.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] A traditional program is usually represented as a series of text instructions, which is reasonable for describing a serial system which pipes data between small, single-purpose tools that receive, process, and return.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs start with an input, perhaps the command line parameters, and illustrate how that data is used and modified.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] The flow of data is explicit, often visually illustrated as a line or pipe.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] In terms of encoding, a dataflow program might be implemented as a hash table, with uniquely identified inputs as the keys, used to look up pointers to the instructions.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] When any operation completes, the program scans down the list of operations until it finds the first operation where all inputs are currently valid, and runs it.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] When that operation finishes, it will typically output data, thereby making another operation become valid.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] For parallel operation, only the list needs to be shared; it is the state of the entire program.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Thus the task of maintaining state is removed from the programmer and given to the language's runtime.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] On machines with a single processor core where an implementation designed for parallel operation would simply introduce overhead, this overhead can be removed completely by using a different runtime.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Some recent dataflow libraries such as Differential/Timely Dataflow have used incremental computing for much more efficient data processing.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] A pioneer dataflow language was BLOck DIagram (BLODI), published in 1961 by John Larry Kelly, Jr., Carol Lochbaum and Victor A.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Vyssotsky for specifying sampled data systems.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] A BLODI specification of functional units (amplifiers, adders, delay lines, etc.) and their interconnections was compiled into a single loop that updated the entire system for one clock tick.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] In a 1966 Ph.D. thesis, *The On-line Graphical Specification of Computer Procedures*, Bert Sutherland created one of the first graphical dataflow programming frameworks in order to make parallel programming easier.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Subsequent dataflow languages were often developed at the large supercomputer labs.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] SISAL, a popular dataflow language developed at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, looks like most statement-driven languages, but variables should be assigned once.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] This allows the compiler to easily identify the inputs and outputs.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] A number of offshoots of SISAL have been developed, including SAC, *Single Assignment C*, which tries to remain as close to the popular C programming language as possible.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] The United States Navy funded development of signal processing graph notation (SPGN) and ACOS starting in the early 1980s.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] This is in use on a number of platforms in the field today.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] A more radical concept is Prograph, in which programs are constructed as graphs onscreen, and variables are replaced entirely with lines linking inputs to outputs.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] Prograph was originally written on the Macintosh, which remained single-processor until the introduction of the DayStar Genesis MP in 1996.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] There are many hardware architectures oriented toward the efficient implementation of dataflow programming models.
[src:apache-beam/dataflow-programming] MIT's tagged token dataflow architecture was designed by Greg Papadopoulos.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:apache-beam/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:apache-beam/pipeline-computing] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:apache-beam/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
